# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: charge-controller
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] The individual cells in a battery pack naturally have somewhat different capacities, and so, over the course of charge and discharge cycles, may be at a different state of charge (SOC).
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] Balancing a multi-cell pack helps to maximize capacity and service life of the pack by working to maintain equivalent state-of-charge of every cell, to the degree possible given their different capacities, over the widest possible range.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] Balancing is only necessary for packs that contain more than one cell in series.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] Parallel cells will naturally balance since they are directly connected to each other, but groups of parallel wired cells, wired in series (parallel-series wiring) must be balanced between cell groups.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] To ensure safe operation and prevent hazardous conditions, the battery management system (BMS) continuously tracks critical parameters like temperature and voltage at the individual cell level, detecting any potential deviations that could lead to failure.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] While current is typically monitored at the pack level to optimize performance, the BMS may include one-shot protection mechanisms at the cell level to rapidly disconnect cells in case of an abnormally high current, such as during a short circuit or other fault conditions.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] Under normal operation, discharging must stop when any cell first runs out of charge even though other cells may still hold significant charge.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] Likewise, charging must stop when any cell reaches its maximum safe charging voltage.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] Failure to do either may cause permanent damage to the cells, or in extreme cases, may drive cells into reverse polarity, cause internal gassing, thermal runaway, or other catastrophic failures.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] If the cells are not balanced, such that the high and low cutoff are at least aligned with the state of the lowest capacity cell, the energy that can be taken from and returned to the battery will be limited.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] Because lithium chemistries often permit flexible membrane structures, lithium cells can be deployed in flexible though sealed bags, which permits higher packing densities within a battery pack.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] When a lithium cell is mistreated, some of the breakdown products (usually of electrolyte chemicals or additives) outgas.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] Such cells will become 'puffy' and are very much on the way to failure.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] In sealed lithium-ion cylindrical-format batteries, the same outgassing has caused rather large pressures (800+ psi has been reported); such cells can explode if not provided with a pressure relief mechanism.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] Compounding the danger is that many lithium cell chemistries include hydrocarbon chemicals (the exact nature of which is typically proprietary), and these are flammable.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] Therefore, in addition to the risk of cell mistreatment potentially causing an explosion, a simple non-explosive leak can cause a fire.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] Most battery chemistries have less dramatic, and less dangerous, failure modes.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] The chemicals in most batteries are often toxic to some degree, but are rarely explosive or flammable; many are corrosive, which accounts for advice to avoid leaving batteries inside equipment for long periods as the batteries may leak and damage the equipment.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] Lead acid batteries are an exception, for charging them generates hydrogen gas, which can explode if exposed to an ignition source (e.g., a lit cigarette ) and such an explosion will spray sulfuric acid in all directions.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] Since this is corrosive and potentially blinding, this is a particular danger.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] In active balancing, the balancer circuit enables transfer of charge between different cells of the battery, i.e., transferring energy from cells with a higher charge to cells with a lower charge.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] The term *battery regulator* typically refers only to devices that perform passive balancing.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] A full BMS might include active balancing as well as temperature monitoring, charging, and other features to maximize the life of a battery pack.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] Typically, the power handled by each DC-DC converter is a few orders of magnitude lower than the power handled by the battery pack as a whole.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] In passive balancing, energy is drawn from the most charged cell and dissipated as heat, usually through resistors.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] Passive balancing equalizes the state of charge at some fixed point—usually either "top balanced", with all cells reaching 100% SOC at the same time; or "bottom balanced", with all cells reaching minimum SOC at the same time.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] Passive balancing is inherently wasteful, with some of the pack's energy spent as heat for the sake of equalizing the state of charge between cells.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] The build-up of waste heat may also limit the rate at which balancing can occur.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] In active balancing, energy may be drawn from the most charged cell and transferred to the least charged cells, e.g., through capacitor-based, inductor-based, or DC-DC converters.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] Active balancing attempts to redistribute energy from cells at full charge to those with a lower state of charge.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] Energy can be bled from a cell at higher SOC by switching a reservoir capacitor in-circuit with the cell, then disconnecting the capacitor and reconnecting it to a cell with lower SOC, or through a DC-to-DC converter connected across the entire pack.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] Due to inefficiencies, some energy is still wasted as heat, but not to the same degree.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] Despite the obvious advantages, the additional cost and complexity of an active balancing topology can be substantial, and doesn't always make sense depending on the application.
[src:charge-controller/battery-balancing] This has the advantage of reducing pack weight slightly and lowering parasitic draw, as well as permitting multi-point balancing.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] A **battery charger**, **recharger**, or simply **charger**, is a device that stores energy in an electric battery by running current through it.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] The charging protocol—how much voltage and current, for how long and what to do when charging is complete—depends on the size and type of the battery being charged.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Some battery types have high tolerance for overcharging after the battery has been fully charged and can be recharged by connection to a constant voltage source or a constant current source, depending on battery type.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Simple chargers of this type must be manually disconnected at the end of the charge cycle.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Other battery types use a timer to cut off when charging should be complete.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Other battery types cannot withstand over-charging, becoming damaged (reduced capacity, reduced lifetime), over heating or even exploding.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] The charger may have temperature or voltage sensing circuits and a microprocessor controller to safely adjust the charging current and voltage, determine the state of charge, and cut off at the end of charge.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Chargers may elevate the output voltage proportionally with current to compensate for impedance in the wires.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] A trickle charger provides a relatively small amount of current, only enough to counteract self-discharge of a battery that is idle for a long time.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Some battery types cannot tolerate trickle charging; attempts to do so may result in damage.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Lithium-ion batteries cannot handle indefinite trickle charging.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Slow battery chargers may take several hours to complete a charge.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] High-rate chargers may restore most capacity much faster, but high-rate chargers can be more than some battery types can tolerate.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Such batteries require active monitoring of the battery to protect it from any abusive use.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Electric vehicles ideally need high-rate chargers.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] For public access, installation of such chargers and the distribution support for them is an issue in the proposed adoption of electric cars.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Charge and discharge rates are often given as *C* or *C-rate*, which is a measure of the rate at which a battery is charged or discharged relative to its capacity.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] The C-rate is defined as the charge or discharge current divided by the battery's capacity to store an electrical charge.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] While rarely stated explicitly, the unit of the C-rate is h−1, equivalent to stating the battery's capacity to store an electrical charge in unit hour times current in the same unit as the charge or discharge current.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] The C-rate is never negative, so whether it describes a charging or discharging process depends on the context.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] For example, for a battery with a capacity of 500 mAh, a discharge rate of 5000 mA (i.e., 5 A) corresponds to a C-rate of 10C, meaning that such a current can discharge 10 such batteries in one hour.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Likewise, for the same battery a charge current of 250 mA corresponds to a C-rate of C/2, meaning that this current will increase the state of charge of this battery by 50% in one hour.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Running current through batteries generates internal heat, roughly proportional to the current involved (a battery's current state of charge, condition / history, etc. are also factors).
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] If the charging process is endothermic (which is the case for Ni–Cd batteries, whereas charging nickel–metal hydride batteries is exothermic) the charging process initially cools the battery, but as it reaches full charge, the cooling effect stops and the cell heats up.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Detecting a temperature rise of 10 °C (18 °F) is one way of determining when to stop charging.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Battery cells which have been built to allow higher C-rates than usual must make provision for increased heating.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] But high C-ratings are attractive to end users because such batteries can be charged more quickly, and produce higher current output in use.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] High C-rates typically require the charger to carefully monitor battery parameters such as terminal voltage and temperature to prevent overcharging and so damage to the cells.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Such high-charging rates are possible only with some battery types.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Others will be damaged or possibly overheat or catch fire.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] For example, an automobile SLI (starting, lighting, ignition) lead–acid battery carries several risks of explosion.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] A simple charger works by supplying a constant DC or pulsed DC power source to a battery being charged.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] A simple charger typically does not alter its output based on charging time or the charge on the battery.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] This simplicity means that a simple charger is inexpensive, but there are tradeoffs.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Typically, a carefully designed simple charger takes longer to charge a battery because it is set to use a lower (i.e., safer) charging rate.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Even so, many batteries left on a simple charger for too long will be weakened or destroyed due to over-charging.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] These chargers also vary in that they can supply either a constant voltage or a constant current, to the battery.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Simple AC-powered battery chargers usually have much higher ripple current and ripple voltage than other kinds of battery chargers because they are inexpensively designed and built.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Generally, when the ripple current is within a battery's manufacturer recommended level, the ripple voltage will also be well within the recommended level.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] The maximum ripple current for a typical 12 V 100 Ah VRLA battery is 5 amperes.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] As long as the ripple current is not excessive (more than 3 to 4 times the level recommended by the battery manufacturer), the expected life of a ripple-charged VRLA battery will be within 3% of the life of a constant DC-charged battery.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Fast chargers make use of control circuitry to rapidly charge the batteries without damaging any of the cells in the battery.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] The control circuitry can be built into the battery (generally for each cell) or in the external charging unit, or split between both.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Most such chargers have a cooling fan to help keep the temperature of the cells at safe levels.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Most fast chargers are also capable of acting as standard overnight chargers if used with standard Ni–MH cells that do not have the special control circuitry.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] To accelerate the charging time and provide continuous charging, an intelligent charger attempts to detect the state of charge and condition of the battery and applies a three-stage charging scheme.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] The following description assumes a sealed lead–acid traction battery at 25 °C (77 °F).
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] The first stage is referred to as "bulk absorption"; the charging current is held high and constant and is limited by the capacity of the charger.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] When the voltage on the battery reaches its outgassing voltage (2.22 volts per cell) the charger switches to the second stage, and the voltage is held constant (2.40 volts per cell).
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] The delivered current declines at the maintained voltage, and when the current reaches less than 0.005C the charger enters its third stage and the charger output is held constant at 2.25 volts per cell.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] In the third stage, the charging current is very small, 0.005C, and at this voltage the battery can be maintained at full charge and compensate for self-discharge.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Inductive battery chargers use electromagnetic induction to charge batteries.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] A charging station sends electromagnetic energy through inductive coupling to an electrical device, which stores the energy in the batteries.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] This is achieved without the need for metal contacts between the charger and the battery.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Inductive battery chargers are commonly used in electric toothbrushes and other devices used in bathrooms.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Because there are no open electrical contacts, there is no risk of electrocution.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Nowadays it is being used to charge wireless phones.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] A smart charger can respond to the condition of a battery and modify its charging parameters accordingly, whereas "dumb" chargers apply a steady voltage, possibly through a fixed resistance.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] It should not be confused with a smart battery that contains a computer chip and communicates digitally with a smart charger about battery condition.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] A smart battery requires a smart charger.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Some smart chargers can also charge "dumb" batteries, which lack any internal electronics.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] The output current of a smart charger depends upon the battery's state.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] An intelligent charger may monitor the battery's voltage, temperature or charge time to determine the optimum charge current or terminate charging.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] For Ni–Cd and Ni–MH batteries, the voltage of the battery increases slowly during the charging process, until the battery is fully charged.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] After that, the voltage *decreases* because of increasing temperature, which indicates to an intelligent charger that the battery is fully charged.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Such chargers are often labeled as a ΔV, "delta-V", or sometimes "delta peak" charger, indicating that they monitor voltage change.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] This can cause even an intelligent charger not to sense that the batteries are already fully charged, and continue charging, the result of which may be overcharging.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Many intelligent chargers employ a variety of cut-off systems to prevent overcharging.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] A typical smart charger fast-charges a battery up to about 85% of its maximum capacity in less than an hour, then switches to trickle charging, which takes several hours to top off the battery to its full capacity.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Several companies have begun making devices that charge batteries using energy from human motion, such as walking.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] An example, made by Tremont Electric, consists of a magnet held between two springs that can charge a battery as the device is moved up and down.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Such products have not yet achieved significant commercial success.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] A pedal-powered charger for mobile phones fitted into desks has been created for installation in public spaces, such as airports, railway stations and universities.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] They have been installed in a number of countries on several continents.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Some chargers use *pulse technology*, in which a series of electrical pulses is fed to the battery.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] The DC pulses have a strictly controlled rise time, pulse width, pulse repetition rate (frequency) and amplitude.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] This technology works with any size and type of battery, including automotive and valve-regulated ones.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] With pulse charging, high instantaneous voltages are applied without overheating the battery.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] In a lead–acid battery, this breaks down lead-sulfate crystals, thus greatly extending the battery service life.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Several kinds of pulse chargers are patented, while others are open source hardware.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Some chargers use pulses to check the current battery state when the charger is first connected, then use constant current charging during fast charge, then use pulse mode to trickle charge it.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Some chargers use "negative pulse charging", also called "reflex charging" or "burp charging".
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] These chargers use both positive and brief negative current pulses.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] There is no significant evidence that negative pulse charging is more effective than ordinary pulse charging.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Solar chargers convert light energy into low-voltage DC current.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] They are generally portable, but can also be fixed mounted.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Fixed mount solar chargers are also known as solar panels.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] These are often connected to the electrical grid via control and interface circuits, whereas portable solar chargers are used off-grid (i.e. cars, boats, or RVs).
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Although portable solar chargers obtain energy only from the sun, they can charge in low light like at sunset.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Portable solar chargers are often used for trickle charging, though some can completely recharge batteries.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] The output of a timer charger is terminated after a predetermined time interval.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Timer chargers were the most common type for high-capacity Ni–Cd cells in the late 1990s to charge low-capacity consumer Ni–Cd cells.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Often a timer charger and set of batteries could be bought as a bundle and the charger time is set for those batteries specifically.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] If batteries of lower capacity are charged, then they would be overcharged, and if batteries of higher capacity were timer-charged, they would not reach full capacity.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Timer based chargers also had the drawback that charging batteries that were not fully discharged would result in over-charging.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] A trickle charger is typically low-current (usually between 5–1,500 mA).
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] They are generally used to charge small capacity batteries (2–30 Ah).
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] They are also used to maintain larger capacity batteries (> 30 Ah) in cars and boats.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] In larger applications, the current of the battery charger is only sufficient to provide trickle current.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Depending on the technology of the trickle charger, it can be left connected to the battery indefinitely.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Some battery types are not suitable for trickle charging.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] For instance, most Li-ion batteries cannot be safely trickle charged and can cause a fire or explosion.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Charge DC (battery) from DC source without conversion to AC.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Modern DC-DC chargers often include isolator and DC-DC converter.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Some may also have BMS (including balance), be bidirectional (jump start primary car battery from secondary battery) and wireless control (Bluetooth, WiFi, NFC, 5G).
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] The most sophisticated chargers are used in critical applications (e.g. military or aviation batteries).
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] These heavy-duty automatic "intelligent charging" systems can be programmed with complex charging cycles specified by the battery manufacturer.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] The best are universal (i.e. can charge all battery types), and include automatic capacity testing and analyzing functions.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Since the Universal Serial Bus specification provides five-volt power, it is possible to use a USB cable to connect a device to a power supply.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Products based on this approach include chargers for cellular phones, portable digital audio players, and tablet computers.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] They may be fully compliant USB peripheral devices or uncontrolled, simple chargers.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Another type of USB charger called "USB (rechargeable) battery" is fitted into the case of standard batteries (1.5 V AA, C, D, and 9 V block) together with a Li-ion rechargeable battery, voltage converter, and USB connector.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Since a battery charger is intended to be connected to a battery, it may not have voltage regulation or filtering of the DC voltage output; it is cheaper to make them that way.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Battery chargers equipped with both voltage regulation and filtering are sometimes termed battery eliminators.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Chargers for car batteries come in varying ratings.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Chargers that are rated up to two amperes may be used to maintain charge on parked vehicle batteries or for small batteries on garden tractors or similar equipment.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] A motorist may keep a charger rated a few amperes to ten or fifteen amperes for maintenance of automobile batteries or to recharge a vehicle battery that has accidentally discharged.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Service stations and commercial garages will have a large charger to fully charge a battery in an hour or two; often these chargers can briefly source the hundreds of amperes required to crank an internal combustion engine starter.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Electric vehicle battery chargers (ECS) come in a variety of brands and characteristics.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] These chargers vary from 1 kW to 22 kW maximum charge rate.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Some use algorithm charge curves, others use constant voltage, constant current.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Some are programmable by the end user through a CAN port, some have dials for maximum voltage and amperage, some are preset to specified battery pack voltage, ampere-hour and chemistry.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] A 10-ampere-hour battery could take 15 hours to reach a fully charged state from a fully discharged condition with a 1-ampere charger as it would require roughly 1.5 times the battery's capacity.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Public EV charging stations often provide 6 kW (host power of 208 to 240 V AC off a 40-ampere circuit).
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] 6 kW will recharge an EV roughly six times faster than 1 kW overnight charging.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Rapid charging results in even faster recharge times and is limited only by available AC power, battery type, and the type of charging system.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Power-factor correction (PFC) chargers can more closely approach the maximum current the plug can deliver, shortening charging time.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Project Better Place was deploying a network of charging stations and subsidizing vehicle battery costs through leases and credits until filing for bankruptcy in May 2013.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Most mobile phone chargers are not really chargers, only power adapters that provide a power source for the charging circuitry which is almost always contained within the mobile phone.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Some higher-end models feature multiple ports which are equipped with a display which indicates output current.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Some support communication protocols for charging parameters such as Qualcomm Quick Charge or MediaTek Pump Express.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Chargers for 12 V automobile auxiliary power outlets may support input voltages of up to 24 or 32 V DC to ensure compatibility, and are sometimes equipped with a display to monitor current or the voltage of the vehicle's electrical system.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] China, the European Union, and other countries are making a national standard on mobile phone chargers using the USB standard.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] In June 2009, 10 of the world's largest mobile phone manufacturers signed a Memorandum of Understanding to develop specifications for and support a microUSB-equipped common external power supply (EPS) for all data-enabled mobile phones sold in the EU.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] On October 22, 2009, the International Telecommunication Union announced that microUSB would be the standard for a universal charger for mobile handsets.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] In October 2022 the EU's Common Charger Directive was approved with the new rules applying to mobile phones and a number of other devices, which came into force in December 2024.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Telecommunications, electric power, and computer uninterruptible power supply facilities may have very large standby battery banks (installed in battery rooms) to maintain critical loads for several hours during interruptions of primary grid power.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Such chargers are permanently installed and equipped with temperature compensation, supervisory alarms for various system faults, and often redundant independent power supplies and redundant rectifier systems.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Chargers for stationary battery plants may have adequate voltage regulation and filtration and sufficient current capacity to allow the battery to be disconnected for maintenance, while the charger supplies the direct current (DC) system load.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] The capacity of the charger is specified to maintain the system load and recharge a completely discharged battery within, say, 8 hours or other intervals.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] A properly designed charger can allow batteries to reach their full cycle life.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Excess charging current, lengthy overcharging, or cell reversal in a multiple cell pack cause damage to cells and limit the life expectancy of a battery.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Most modern cell phones, laptop and tablet computers, and most electric vehicles use lithium-ion batteries.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] These batteries last longest if the battery is frequently charged; fully discharging the cells will degrade their capacity relatively quickly, but most such batteries are used in equipment which can sense the approach of full discharge and discontinue equipment use.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] When stored after charging, lithium battery cells degrade more while fully charged than if they are only 40–50% charged.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] As with all battery types, degradation also occurs faster at higher temperatures.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Degradation in lithium-ion batteries is caused by an increased internal battery resistance often due to the cell oxidation.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] This decreases the efficiency of the battery, resulting in less net current available to be drawn from the battery.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] However, if Li-ion cells are discharged below a certain voltage a chemical reaction occurs that make them dangerous if recharged, which is why many such batteries in consumer goods now have an "electronic fuse" that permanently disables them if the voltage falls below a set level.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] The electronic fuse circuitry draws a small amount of current from the battery, which means that if a laptop battery is left for a long time without charging it, and with a very low initial state of charge, the battery may be permanently destroyed.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Motor vehicles, such as boats, RVs, ATVs, motorcycles, cars, trucks, etc. have used lead–acid batteries.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] These batteries employ a sulfuric acid electrolyte and can generally be charged and discharged without exhibiting memory effect, though sulfation (a chemical reaction in the battery which deposits a layer of sulfates on the lead) will occur over time.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Typically sulfated batteries are simply replaced with new batteries, and the old ones recycled.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Lead–acid batteries will experience substantially longer life when a maintenance charger is used to "float charge" the battery.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] This prevents the battery from ever being below 100% charge, preventing sulfate from forming.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Proper temperature compensated float voltage should be used to achieve the best results.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Battery charging technology is developing to support the increasing demands of electric vehicles (EVs), consumer electronics, and sustainable energy systems.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Modern chargers may feature Internet of things (IoT) connectivity for real-time monitoring, adaptive charging protocols, remote management, predictive maintenance, and may enhance safety and efficiency.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Artificial intelligence (AI) is being integrated into battery management systems to optimize charging rates, predict battery health, extend usable life, and maximize energy efficiency.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] As a result of electric mobility and smart device proliferation, the global battery charger market is projected (as of 2025) to see significant growth over the following decade.
[src:charge-controller/battery-charger] Smart chargers integrating IoT, AI, and adaptive features are expected to outpace traditional models globally.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] An **electric battery** is a source of electric power consisting of one or more electrochemical cells with external connections for powering electrical devices.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] When a battery is supplying power, its positive terminal is the cathode and its negative terminal is the anode.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The terminal marked negative is the source of electrons.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] When a battery is connected to an external electric load, those negatively charged electrons flow through the circuit and reach the positive terminal, thus causing a redox reaction by attracting positively charged ions, or cations.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Thus, higher energy reactants are converted to lower energy products, and the free-energy difference is delivered to the external circuit as electrical energy.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Historically the term "battery" specifically referred to a device composed of multiple cells; however, the usage has evolved to include devices composed of a single cell.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Primary (single-use or "disposable") batteries are used once and discarded, as the electrode materials are irreversibly changed during discharge; a common example is the alkaline battery used for flashlights and a multitude of portable electronic devices.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Secondary (rechargeable) batteries can be discharged and recharged multiple times using an applied electric current; the original composition of the electrodes can be restored by reverse current.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Examples include the lead–acid automotive battery used in internal combustion engine vehicles, and lithium-ion batteries used for portable electronics and electric cars.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Batteries come in many shapes and sizes, from miniature cells used to power hearing aids and wristwatches to, at the largest extreme, huge battery banks the size of rooms that provide standby or emergency power for telephone exchanges and computer data centers.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Batteries have much lower specific energy (energy per unit mass) than common fuels such as gasoline.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] In automobiles, this is somewhat offset by the higher efficiency of electric motors in converting electrical energy to mechanical work, compared to combustion engines.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Benjamin Franklin first used the term "battery" in 1749 when he was doing experiments with electricity using a set of linked Leyden jar capacitors.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Franklin grouped a number of the jars into what he described as a "battery", using the military term for weapons functioning together.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] By multiplying the number of holding vessels, a stronger charge could be stored, and more power would be available on discharge.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Italian physicist Alessandro Volta built and described the first electrochemical battery, the voltaic pile, in 1800.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] This was a stack of copper and zinc plates, separated by brine-soaked paper disks, that could produce a steady current for a considerable length of time.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Volta did not understand that the voltage was due to chemical reactions.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] He thought that his cells were an inexhaustible source of energy, and that the associated corrosion effects at the electrodes were a mere nuisance, rather than an unavoidable consequence of their operation, as Michael Faraday showed in 1834.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Although early batteries were of great value for experimental purposes, in practice their voltages fluctuated and they could not provide a large current for a sustained period.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The Daniell cell, invented in 1836 by British chemist John Frederic Daniell, was the first practical source of electricity, becoming an industry standard and seeing widespread adoption as a power source for electrical telegraph networks.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] It consisted of a copper pot filled with a copper sulfate solution, in which was immersed an unglazed earthenware container filled with sulfuric acid and a zinc electrode.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] These wet cells used liquid electrolytes, which were prone to leakage and spillage if not handled correctly.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Many used glass jars to hold their components, which made them fragile and potentially dangerous.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] These characteristics made wet cells unsuitable for portable appliances.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Near the end of the nineteenth century, the invention of dry cell batteries, which replaced the liquid electrolyte with a paste, made portable electrical devices practical.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Batteries in vacuum tube devices historically used a wet cell for the "A" battery (to provide power to the filament) and a dry cell for the "B" battery (to provide the plate voltage).
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Between 2010 and 2018, battery demand grew by 30% annually, reaching a total of 180 GWh in 2018.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Conservatively, the growth rate is expected to be maintained at an estimated 25%, culminating in demand reaching 2600 GWh in 2030.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] In addition, cost reductions are expected to further increase the demand to as much as 3562 GWh.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Important reasons for this high rate of growth of the electric battery industry include the electrification of transport, and large-scale deployment in electricity grids, supported by decarbonization initiatives.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Distributed electric batteries, such as those used in battery electric vehicles (vehicle-to-grid) and in home energy storage with smart metering and that are connected to smart grids for demand response are active participants in smart power supply grids.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Secondary use of partially depleted batteries can add to the overall utility of electric batteries by reducing energy storage costs and emission impact due to longer service life.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] In this use, vehicle electric batteries that have their battery capacity reduced to less than 80% (usually after 5–8 years of service) are repurposed for use in backup supplies or renewable energy storage systems.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Grid scale energy storage envisages the large-scale use of batteries to collect and store energy from the grid or a power plant and then discharge that energy at a later time to provide electricity or other grid services when needed.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Grid scale energy storage (either turnkey or distributed) are important components of smart power supply grids.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The advent of computational modeling has revolutionized battery materials design, enabling high-throughput screening and atomistic simulations that accelerate the discovery of novel electrolytes and electrodes, moving beyond traditional trial-and-error approaches.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Batteries convert chemical energy directly to electrical energy.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] In many cases, the electrical energy released is the difference in the cohesive or bond energies of the metals, oxides, or molecules undergoing the electrochemical reaction.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] For instance, energy can be stored in Zn or Li, which are high-energy metals because they are not stabilized by d-electron bonding, unlike transition metals.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Batteries are designed so that the energetically favorable redox reaction can occur only when electrons move through the external part of the circuit.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] A battery consists of some number of voltaic cells.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Each cell consists of two half-cells connected in series by a conductive electrolyte containing metal *cations*.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] One half-cell includes electrolyte and the negative electrode, the electrode to which anions (negatively charged ions) migrate; the other half-cell includes electrolyte and the positive electrode, to which cations (positively charged ions) migrate.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Cations are reduced (electrons are added) at the cathode, while metal atoms are oxidized (electrons are removed) at the anode.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Some cells use different electrolytes for each half-cell; then a separator is used to prevent mixing of the electrolytes while allowing ions to flow between half-cells to complete the electrical circuit.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Each half-cell has an electromotive force (*emf*, measured in volts) relative to a standard.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The net emf of the cell is the difference between the emfs of its half-cells.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Thus, if the electrodes have emfs ${\mathcal {E}}_{1}$ and ${\mathcal {E}}_{2}$ , then the net emf is ${\mathcal {E}}_{2}-{\mathcal {E}}_{1}$ ; in other words, the net emf is the difference between the reduction potentials of the half-reactions.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The electrical driving force or $\displaystyle {\Delta V_{\text{bat}}}$ across the terminals of a cell is known as the *terminal voltage (difference)* and is measured in volts.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The terminal voltage of a cell that is neither charging nor discharging is called the open-circuit voltage and equals the emf of the cell.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Because of internal resistance, the terminal voltage of a cell that is discharging is smaller in magnitude than the open-circuit voltage and the terminal voltage of a cell that is charging exceeds the open-circuit voltage.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] An ideal cell has negligible internal resistance, so it would maintain a constant terminal voltage of ${\mathcal {E}}$ until exhausted, then dropping to zero.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] If such a cell maintained 1.5 volts and produced a charge of one coulomb then on complete discharge it would have performed 1.5 joules of work.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] In actual cells, the internal resistance increases under discharge and the open-circuit voltage also decreases under discharge.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] If the voltage and resistance are plotted against time, the resulting graphs typically are a curve; the shape of the curve varies according to the chemistry and internal arrangement employed.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The voltage developed across a cell's terminals depends on the energy release of the chemical reactions of its electrodes and electrolyte.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Alkaline and zinc–carbon cells have different chemistries, but approximately the same emf of 1.5 volts; likewise NiCd and NiMH cells have different chemistries, but approximately the same emf of 1.2 volts.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The high electrochemical potential changes in the reactions of lithium compounds give lithium cells emfs of 3 volts or more.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Almost any liquid or moist object that has enough ions to be electrically conductive can serve as the electrolyte for a cell.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] As a novelty or science demonstration, it is possible to insert two electrodes made of different metals into a lemon, potato, etc. and generate small amounts of electricity.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] A voltaic pile can be made from two coins (such as a nickel and a penny) and a piece of paper towel dipped in salt water.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Such a pile generates a very low voltage but, when many are stacked in series, they can replace normal batteries for a short time.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Some types of primary batteries used, for example, for telegraph circuits, were restored to operation by replacing the electrodes.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Secondary batteries are not indefinitely rechargeable due to dissipation of the active materials, loss of electrolyte and internal corrosion.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Primary batteries, or primary cells, can produce current immediately on assembly.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] These are most commonly used in portable devices that have low current drain, are used only intermittently, or are used well away from an alternative power source, such as in alarm and communication circuits where other electric power is only intermittently available.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Disposable primary cells cannot be reliably recharged, since the chemical reactions are not easily reversible and active materials may not return to their original forms.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Battery manufacturers recommend against attempting to recharge primary cells.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] In general, these have higher energy densities than rechargeable batteries, but disposable batteries do not fare well under high-drain applications with loads under 75 ohms (75 Ω).
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Common types of disposable batteries include zinc–carbon batteries and alkaline batteries.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Secondary batteries, also known as *secondary cells*, or *rechargeable batteries*, must be charged before first use; they are usually assembled with active materials in the discharged state.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Rechargeable batteries are (re)charged by applying electric current, which reverses the chemical reactions that occur during discharge/use.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Devices to supply the appropriate current are called chargers.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The oldest form of rechargeable battery is the lead–acid battery, which are widely used in automotive and boating applications.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] This technology contains liquid electrolyte in an unsealed container, requiring that the battery be kept upright and the area be well ventilated to ensure safe dispersal of the hydrogen gas it produces during overcharging.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The lead–acid battery is relatively heavy for the amount of electrical energy it can supply.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Its low manufacturing cost and its high surge current levels make it common where its capacity (over approximately 10 Ah) is more important than weight and handling issues.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] A common application is the modern car battery, which can, in general, deliver a peak current of 450 amperes.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Many types of electrochemical cells have been produced, with varying chemical processes and designs, including galvanic cells, electrolytic cells, fuel cells, flow cells and voltaic piles.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] A *wet cell* battery has a liquid electrolyte.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Other names are *flooded cell*, since the liquid covers all internal parts or *vented cell*, since gases produced during operation can escape to the air.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Wet cells were a precursor to dry cells and are commonly used as a learning tool for electrochemistry.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] They can be built with common laboratory supplies, such as beakers, for demonstrations of how electrochemical cells work.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] A particular type of wet cell known as a concentration cell is important in understanding corrosion.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Wet cells may be primary cells (non-rechargeable) or secondary cells (rechargeable).
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Originally, all practical primary batteries, such as the Daniell cell, were built as open-top glass jar wet cells.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Other primary wet cells are the Leclanche cell, Grove cell, Bunsen cell, Chromic acid cell, Clark cell, and Weston cell.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The Leclanche cell chemistry was adapted to the first dry cells.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Wet cells are still used in automobile batteries and in industry for standby power for switchgear, telecommunication or large uninterruptible power supplies, but in many places batteries with gel cells have been used instead.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] These applications commonly use lead–acid or nickel–cadmium cells.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Molten salt batteries are primary or secondary batteries that use a molten salt as electrolyte.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] They operate at high temperatures and must be well insulated to retain heat.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] A *dry cell* uses a paste electrolyte, with only enough moisture to allow current to flow.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Unlike a wet cell, a dry cell can operate in any orientation without spilling, as it contains no free liquid, making it suitable for portable equipment.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] By comparison, the first wet cells were typically fragile glass containers with lead rods hanging from the open top and needed careful handling to avoid spillage.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Lead–acid batteries did not achieve the safety and portability of the dry cell until the development of the gel battery.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] A common dry cell is the zinc–carbon battery, sometimes called the dry Leclanché cell, with a nominal voltage of 1.5 volts, the same as the alkaline battery (since both use the same zinc–manganese dioxide combination).
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] A standard dry cell comprises a zinc anode, usually in the form of a cylindrical pot, with a carbon cathode in the form of a central rod.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The electrolyte is ammonium chloride in the form of a paste next to the zinc anode.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The remaining space between the electrolyte and carbon cathode is taken up by a second paste consisting of ammonium chloride and manganese dioxide, the latter acting as a depolariser.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] In some designs, the ammonium chloride is replaced by zinc chloride.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] A reserve battery can be stored unassembled (unactivated and supplying no power) for a long period (perhaps years).
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] When the battery is needed, then it is assembled (e.g., by adding electrolyte); once assembled, the battery is charged and ready to work.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] For example, a battery for an electronic artillery fuze might be activated by the impact of firing a gun.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The acceleration breaks a capsule of electrolyte that activates the battery and powers the fuze's circuits.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Reserve batteries are usually designed for a short service life (seconds or minutes) after long storage (years).
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] A water-activated battery for oceanographic instruments or military applications becomes activated on immersion in water.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The solid-state battery is also said to have "three times the energy density", increasing its useful life in electric vehicles, for example.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] It should also be more ecologically sound since the technology uses less expensive, earth-friendly materials such as sodium extracted from seawater.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Sony has developed a biological battery that generates electricity from sugar in a way that is similar to the processes observed in living organisms.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The battery generates electricity through the use of enzymes that break down carbohydrates.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The sealed valve regulated lead–acid battery (VRLA battery) is popular in the automotive industry as a replacement for the lead–acid wet cell.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The VRLA battery uses an immobilized sulfuric acid electrolyte, reducing the chance of leakage and extending shelf life.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] VRLA batteries immobilize the electrolyte.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Other portable rechargeable batteries include several sealed "dry cell" types, that are useful in applications such as mobile phones and laptop computers.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Cells of this type (in order of increasing power density and cost) include nickel–cadmium (NiCd), nickel–zinc (NiZn), nickel–metal hydride (NiMH), and lithium-ion (Li-ion) cells.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Li-ion has by far the highest share of the dry cell rechargeable market.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] NiMH has replaced NiCd in most applications due to its higher capacity, but NiCd remains in use in power tools, two-way radios, and medical equipment.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Low self-discharge (LSD) allows secondary cells to be charged prior to shipping.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Lithium–sulfur batteries were used on the longest and highest solar-powered flight.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Batteries of all types are manufactured in consumer and industrial grades.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Standard-format batteries are inserted into battery holder in the device that uses them.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] When a device does not uses standard-format batteries, they are typically combined into a custom battery pack which holds multiple batteries in addition to features such as a battery management system and battery isolator which ensure that the batteries within are charged and discharged evenly.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Primary batteries readily available to consumers range from tiny button cells used for electric watches, to the No.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] 6 cell used for signal circuits or other long duration applications.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Secondary cells are made in very large sizes; very large batteries can power a submarine or stabilize an electrical grid and help level out peak loads.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] As of 2017, the world's largest battery was built in South Australia by Tesla.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] A battery in Hebei Province, China, which can store 36 MWh of electricity was built in 2013 at a cost of $500 million.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Another large battery, composed of Ni–Cd cells, was in Fairbanks, Alaska.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] It covered 2,000 square metres (22,000 sq ft)—bigger than a football pitch—and weighed 1,300 tonnes.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] It was manufactured by ABB to provide backup power in the event of a blackout.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The battery can provide 40 MW of power for up to seven minutes.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Sodium–sulfur batteries have been used to store wind power.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] A 4.4 MWh battery system that can deliver 11 MW for 25 minutes stabilizes the output of the Auwahi wind farm in Hawaii.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Many important cell properties, such as voltage, energy density, flammability, available cell constructions, operating temperature range and shelf life, are dictated by battery chemistry.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] A battery's characteristics may vary over load cycle, over charge cycle, and over lifetime due to many factors including internal chemistry, current drain, and temperature.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] At low temperatures, a battery cannot deliver as much power.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] As such, in cold climates, some car owners install battery warmers, which are small electric heating pads that keep the car battery warm.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] A battery's *capacity* is the amount of electric charge it can deliver at a voltage that does not drop below the specified terminal voltage.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The more electrode material contained in the cell the greater its capacity.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] A small cell has less capacity than a larger cell with the same chemistry, although they develop the same open-circuit voltage.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Capacity is usually stated in ampere-hours (A·h) (mAh for small batteries).
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The rated capacity of a battery is usually expressed as the product of 20 hours multiplied by the current that a new battery can consistently supply for 20 hours at 20 °C (68 °F), while remaining above a specified terminal voltage per cell.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] For example, a battery rated at 100 A·h can deliver 5 A over a 20-hour period at room temperature.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The fraction of the stored charge that a battery can deliver depends on multiple factors, including battery chemistry, the rate at which the charge is delivered (current), the required terminal voltage, the storage period, ambient temperature and other factors.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The higher the discharge rate, the lower the capacity.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] is the capacity when discharged at a rate of 1 amp.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] is the amount of time (in hours) that a battery can sustain.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Charged batteries (rechargeable or disposable) lose charge by internal self-discharge over time although not discharged, due to the presence of generally irreversible *side reactions* that consume charge carriers without producing current.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The rate of self-discharge depends upon battery chemistry and construction, typically from months to years for significant loss.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] When batteries are recharged, additional side reactions reduce capacity for subsequent discharges.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] After enough recharges, in essence all capacity is lost and the battery stops producing power.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Internal energy losses and limitations on the rate that ions pass through the electrolyte cause battery efficiency to vary.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Above a minimum threshold, discharging at a low rate delivers more of the battery's capacity than at a higher rate.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Installing batteries with varying A·h ratings changes operating time, but not device operation unless load limits are exceeded.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] High-drain loads such as digital cameras can reduce total capacity of rechargeable or disposable batteries.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] For example, a battery rated at 2 A·h for a 10- or 20-hour discharge would not sustain a current of 1 A for a full two hours as its stated capacity suggests.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The C-rate is a measure of the rate at which a battery is being charged or discharged.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] It is defined as the current through the battery divided by the theoretical current draw under which the battery would deliver its nominal rated capacity in one hour.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Because of internal resistance loss and the chemical processes inside the cells, a battery rarely delivers nameplate rated capacity in only one hour.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Typically, maximum capacity is found at a low C-rate, and charging or discharging at a higher C-rate reduces the usable life and capacity of a battery.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Manufacturers often publish datasheets with graphs showing capacity versus C-rate curves.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] C-rate is also used as a rating on batteries to indicate the maximum current that a battery can safely deliver in a circuit.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Standards for rechargeable batteries generally rate the capacity and charge cycles over a 4-hour (0.25C), 8 hour (0.125C) or longer discharge time.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Types intended for special purposes, such as in a computer uninterruptible power supply, may be rated by manufacturers for discharge periods much less than one hour (1C) but may suffer from limited cycle life.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] In 2009 experimental lithium iron phosphate (LiFePO 4) battery technology provided the fastest charging and energy delivery, discharging all its energy into a load in 10 to 20 seconds.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] In 2024 a prototype battery for electric cars that could charge from 10% to 80% in five minutes was demonstrated, and a Chinese company claimed that car batteries it had introduced charged 10% to 80% in 10.5 minutes—the fastest batteries available—compared to Tesla's 15 minutes to half-charge.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Battery life (or lifetime) has two meanings for rechargeable batteries but only one for non-chargeable batteries.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] It can be used to describe the length of time a device can run on a fully charged battery—this is also unambiguously termed "endurance".
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] For a rechargeable battery it may also be used for the number of charge/discharge cycles possible before the cells fail to operate satisfactorily—this is also termed "lifespan".
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The term *shelf life* is used to describe how long a battery will retain its performance between manufacture and use.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Available capacity of all batteries drops with decreasing temperature.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] In contrast to most of today's batteries, the Zamboni pile, invented in 1812, offers a very long service life without refurbishment or recharge, although it can supply very little current (nanoamps).
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The Oxford Electric Bell has been ringing almost continuously since 1840 on its original pair of batteries, thought to be Zamboni piles.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Disposable batteries typically lose 8–20% of their original charge per year when stored at room temperature (20–30 °C).
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] This is known as the "self-discharge" rate, and is due to non-current-producing "side" chemical reactions that occur within the cell even when no load is applied.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The rate of side reactions is reduced for batteries stored at lower temperatures, although some can be damaged by freezing and storing in a fridge will not meaningfully prolong shelf life and risks damaging condensation.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Old rechargeable batteries self-discharge more rapidly than disposable alkaline batteries, especially nickel-based batteries; a freshly charged nickel cadmium (NiCd) battery loses 10% of its charge in the first 24 hours, and thereafter discharges at a rate of about 10% a month.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] However, newer low self-discharge nickel–metal hydride (NiMH) batteries and modern lithium designs display a lower self-discharge rate (but still higher than for primary batteries).
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The active material on the battery plates changes chemical composition on each charge and discharge cycle; active material may be lost due to physical changes of volume, further limiting the number of times the battery can be recharged.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Most nickel-based batteries are partially discharged when purchased, and must be charged before first use.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Newer NiMH batteries are ready to be used when purchased, and have only 15% discharge in a year.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Some deterioration occurs on each charge–discharge cycle.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Degradation usually occurs because electrolyte migrates away from the electrodes or because active material detaches from the electrodes.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Low-capacity NiMH batteries (1,700–2,000 mA·h) can be charged some 1,000 times, whereas high-capacity NiMH batteries (above 2,500 mA·h) last about 500 cycles.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] NiCd batteries tend to be rated for 1,000 cycles before their internal resistance permanently increases beyond usable values.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Fast charging increases component changes, shortening battery lifespan.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] If a charger cannot detect when the battery is fully charged then overcharging is likely, damaging it.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] NiCd cells, if used in a particular repetitive manner, may show a decrease in capacity called "memory effect".
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The effect can be avoided with simple practices.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] NiMH cells, although similar in chemistry, suffer less from memory effect.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Automotive lead–acid rechargeable batteries must endure stress due to vibration, shock, and temperature range.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Because of these stresses and sulfation of their lead plates, few automotive batteries last beyond six years of regular use.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Automotive starting (SLI: *Starting, Lighting, Ignition*) batteries have many thin plates to maximize current.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] In general, the thicker the plates the longer the life.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] They are typically discharged only slightly before recharge.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] "Deep-cycle" lead–acid batteries such as those used in electric golf carts have much thicker plates to extend longevity.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The main benefit of the lead–acid battery is its low cost; its main drawbacks are large size and weight for a given capacity and voltage.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Lead–acid batteries should never be discharged to below 20% of their capacity, because internal resistance will cause heat and damage when they are recharged.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Deep-cycle lead–acid systems often use a low-charge warning light or a low-charge power cut-off switch to prevent the type of damage that will shorten the battery's life.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Battery life can be extended by storing the batteries at a low temperature, as in a refrigerator or freezer, which slows the side reactions.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Such storage can extend the life of alkaline batteries by about 5%; rechargeable batteries can hold their charge much longer, depending upon type.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] To reach their maximum voltage, batteries must be returned to room temperature; discharging an alkaline battery at 250 mA at 0 °C is only half as efficient as at 20 °C.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Alkaline battery manufacturers such as Duracell do not recommend refrigerating batteries.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] A battery explosion is generally caused by misuse or malfunction, such as attempting to recharge a primary (non-rechargeable) battery, or a short circuit.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] When a battery is recharged at an excessive rate, an explosive gas mixture of hydrogen and oxygen may be produced faster than it can escape from within the battery (e.g. through a built-in vent), leading to pressure build-up and eventual bursting of the battery case.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] In extreme cases, battery chemicals may spray violently from the casing and cause injury.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] An expert summary of the problem indicates that this type uses "liquid electrolytes to transport lithium ions between the anode and the cathode.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] If a battery cell is charged too quickly, it can cause a short circuit, leading to explosions and fires".
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Car batteries are most likely to explode when a short circuit generates very large currents.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Such batteries produce hydrogen, which is very explosive, when they are overcharged (because of electrolysis of the water in the electrolyte).
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] During normal use, the amount of overcharging is usually very small and generates little hydrogen, which dissipates quickly.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] However, when "jump starting" a car, the high current can cause the rapid release of large volumes of hydrogen, which can be ignited explosively by a nearby spark, e.g. when disconnecting a jumper cable.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Overcharging (attempting to charge a battery beyond its electrical capacity) can also lead to a battery explosion, in addition to leakage or irreversible damage.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] It may also cause damage to the charger or device in which the overcharged battery is later used.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Disposing of a battery via incineration may cause an explosion as steam builds up within the sealed case.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Many battery chemicals are corrosive, poisonous or both.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] If leakage occurs, either spontaneously or through accident, the chemicals released may be dangerous.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] For example, disposable batteries often use a zinc "can" both as a reactant and as the container to hold the other reagents.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] If this kind of battery is over-discharged, the reagents can emerge through the cardboard and plastic that form the remainder of the container.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The active chemical leakage can then damage or disable the equipment that the batteries power.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] For this reason, many electronic device manufacturers recommend removing the batteries from devices that will not be used for extended periods of time.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Many types of batteries employ toxic materials such as lead, mercury, and cadmium as an electrode or electrolyte.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] When each battery reaches end of life it must be disposed of to prevent environmental damage.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Batteries are one form of electronic waste (e-waste).
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] E-waste recycling services recover toxic substances, which can then be used for new batteries.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Of the nearly three billion batteries purchased annually in the United States, about 179,000 tons end up in landfills across the country.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Batteries may be harmful or fatal if swallowed.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Small button cells can be swallowed, in particular by young children.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] While in the digestive tract, the battery's electrical discharge may lead to tissue damage; such damage is occasionally serious and can lead to death.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Ingested disk batteries do not usually cause problems unless they become lodged in the gastrointestinal tract.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The most common place for disk batteries to become lodged is the esophagus, resulting in clinical sequelae.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Batteries that successfully traverse the esophagus are unlikely to lodge elsewhere.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The likelihood that a disk battery will lodge in the esophagus is a function of the patient's age and the size of the battery.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Older children do not have problems with batteries smaller than 21–23 mm.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Liquefaction necrosis may occur because sodium hydroxide is generated by the current produced by the battery (usually at the anode).
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Perforation has occurred as rapidly as 6 hours after ingestion.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Some manufacturers add a bittering agent to their batteries to discourage swallowing.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] Legislation around electric batteries includes such topics as safe disposal and recycling.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] In response to reported accidents and failures, occasionally ignition or explosion, recalls of devices using lithium-ion batteries have become more common in recent years.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] In the United States, the Mercury-Containing and Rechargeable Battery Management Act of 1996 banned the sale of mercury-containing batteries, enacted uniform labeling requirements for rechargeable batteries and required that rechargeable batteries be easily removable.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] California and New York City prohibit the disposal of rechargeable batteries in solid waste.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The rechargeable battery industry operates nationwide recycling programs in the United States and Canada, with dropoff points at local retailers.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] The Battery Directive of the European Union has similar requirements, in addition to requiring increased recycling of batteries and promoting research on improved battery recycling methods.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] In accordance with this directive all batteries to be sold within the EU must be marked with the "collection symbol" (a crossed-out wheeled bin).
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] This must cover at least 3% of the surface of prismatic batteries and 1.5% of the surface of cylindrical batteries.
[src:charge-controller/battery-electricity] On 9 December 2022, the European Parliament reached an agreement to force, from 2026, manufacturers to design all electrical appliances sold in the EU (and not used predominantly in wet conditions) so that consumers can easily remove and replace batteries themselves.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] A battery pack built together with a BMS with an external communication data bus is a smart battery pack.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] A smart battery pack must be charged by a smart battery charger.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] Battery thermal management systems can be either passive or active, and the cooling medium can either be air, liquid, or some form of phase change.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] Air cooling is advantageous in its simplicity.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] Such systems can be passive, relying only on the convection of the surrounding air, or active, using fans for airflow.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] Commercially, the Honda Insight and Toyota Prius both use active air cooling of their battery systems.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] The major disadvantage of air cooling is its inefficiency.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] Large amounts of power must be used to operate the cooling mechanism, far more than active liquid cooling.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] The additional components of the cooling mechanism also add weight to the BMS, reducing the efficiency of batteries used for transportation.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] Liquid cooling has a higher natural cooling potential than air cooling as liquid coolants tend to have higher thermal conductivities than air.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] The batteries can either be directly submerged in the coolant or the coolant can flow through the BMS without directly contacting the battery.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] Indirect cooling has the potential to create large thermal gradients across the BMS due to the increased length of the cooling channels.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] This can be reduced by pumping the coolant faster through the system, creating a tradeoff between pumping speed and thermal consistency.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] The central controller of a BMS communicates internally with its hardware operating at a cell level, or externally with high level hardware such as laptops or an HMI.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] Low-voltage centralized BMSes mostly do not have any internal communications.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] Distributed or modular BMSes must use some low-level internal cell–controller (modular architecture) or controller–controller (distributed architecture) communication.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] These types of communications are difficult, especially for high-voltage systems.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] The problem is the voltage shift between cells.The first cell ground signal may be hundreds of volts higher than the other cell ground signal.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] Apart from software protocols, there are two known ways of hardware communication for voltage shifting systems, optical-isolator and wireless communication.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] Another restriction for internal communications is the maximum number of cells.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] For modular architecture, most hardware is limited to a maximum of 255 nodes.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] For high-voltage systems the seeking time of all cells is another restriction, limiting minimum bus speeds and losing some hardware options.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] The cost of modular systems is important, because it may be comparable to the cell price.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] To bypass power limitations of existing USB cables due to heat from electric current, communication protocols implemented in mobile phone chargers for negotiating an elevated voltage have been developed, the most widely used of which are Qualcomm Quick Charge and MediaTek Pump Express.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] More recently, the USB Power Delivery standard aims for a universal negotiation protocol across devices of up to 240 watts.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] A BMS may also feature a precharge system allowing a safe way to connect the battery to different loads and eliminating the excessive inrush currents to load capacitors.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] The connection to loads is normally controlled through electromagnetic relays called contactors.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] The precharge circuit can be either power resistors connected in series with the loads until the capacitors are charged.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] Alternatively, a switched mode power supply connected in parallel to loads can be used to charge the voltage of the load circuit up to a level close enough to the battery voltage in to allow closing the contactors between the battery and load circuit.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] A BMS may have a circuit that can check whether a relay is already closed before recharging (due to welding for example) to prevent inrush currents from occurring.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] In order to maximize the battery's capacity, and to prevent localized under-charging or over-charging, the BMS may actively ensure that all the cells that compose the battery are kept at the same voltage or State of Charge, through balancing.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] Some chargers accomplish the balance by charging each cell independently.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] This is often performed by the BMS and not the charger (which typically provides only the bulk charge current, and does not interact with the pack at the cell-group level), e.g., e-bike and hoverboard chargers.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] In this method, the BMS will request a lower charge current (such as EV batteries), or will shut-off the charging input (typical in portable electronics) through the use of transistor circuitry while balancing is in effect (to prevent over-charging cells).
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] Centralized BMSs are the most economical, least expandable, and are plagued by a multitude of wires.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] Distributed BMSs are the most expensive, simplest to install, and offer the cleanest assembly.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] Modular BMSes offer a compromise of the features and problems of the other two topologies.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] In the case of electric or hybrid vehicles, the BMS is only a subsystem and cannot work as a stand-alone device.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] It must communicate with at least a charger (or charging infrastructure), a load, thermal management and emergency shutdown subsystems.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] Therefore, in a good vehicle design the BMS is tightly integrated with those subsystems.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] Some small mobile applications (such as medical equipment carts, motorized wheelchairs, scooters, and forklifts) often have external charging hardware, however the on board BMS must still have tight design integration with the external charger.
[src:charge-controller/battery-management-system] Various battery balancing methods are in use, some of them based on state of charge theory.
[src:charge-controller/boat] A **boat** is a watercraft of a large range of types and sizes, but generally smaller than a ship, which is distinguished by its larger size or capacity, its shape, or its ability to carry boats.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Small boats are typically used on inland waterways such as rivers and lakes, or in protected coastal areas.
[src:charge-controller/boat] However, some boats (such as whaleboats) were intended for offshore use.
[src:charge-controller/boat] In modern naval terms, a boat is a vessel small enough to be carried aboard a ship.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Submarines are referred to as *boats* rather than *ships* regardless of their size.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Boats vary in proportions and construction methods according to their intended purpose, available materials, or local traditions.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Canoes have been used since prehistoric times and remain in use throughout the world for transportation, fishing, and sport.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Fishing boats vary widely in style, partly to match local conditions.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Pleasure craft used in recreational boating include ski boats, pontoon boats, and sailboats.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Houseboats may be used for vacationing or long-term residence.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Lighters are used to move cargo to and from large ships unable to get close to shore.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Lifeboats have rescue and safety functions.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Boats can be propelled by manpower (e.g., rowboats and paddle boats), wind (e.g., sailboats), and inboard/outboard motors (including gasoline, diesel, and electric).
[src:charge-controller/boat] The earliest watercraft are considered to have been rafts.
[src:charge-controller/boat] These would have been used for voyages such as the settlement of Australia, which occurred sometime between 50,000 and 60,000 years ago.
[src:charge-controller/boat] A boat differs from a raft by obtaining its buoyancy by having most of its structure exclude water with a waterproof layer, e.g., the planks of a wooden hull, the hide covering (or tarred canvas) of a currach.
[src:charge-controller/boat] In contrast, a raft is buoyant because it joins components that are themselves buoyant, such as logs, bamboo poles, bundles of reeds, and floats (such as inflated hides, sealed pottery containers, or, in a modern context, empty oil drums).
[src:charge-controller/boat] The key difference between a raft and a boat is that the former is a "flow through" structure, with waves able to pass up through it.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Consequently, except for short river crossings, a raft is not a practical means of transport in colder regions of the world, as the users would be at risk of hypothermia.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Today, that climatic limitation restricts rafts to between 40° north and 40° south, with similar boundaries in the past that have shifted as the world's climate has varied.
[src:charge-controller/boat] The earliest boats may have been either dugouts or hide boats.
[src:charge-controller/boat] The oldest recovered boat in the world, the Pesse canoe, found in the Netherlands, is a dugout made from the hollowed tree trunk of a *Pinus sylvestris* that was constructed somewhere between 8200 and 7600 BC.
[src:charge-controller/boat] This canoe is exhibited in the Drents Museum in Assen, Netherlands.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Other very old dugout boats have also been recovered.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Hide boats, made from covering a framework with animal skins, could be equally as old as logboats, but such a structure is much less likely to survive in an archaeological context.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Plank-built boats are considered, in most cases, to have developed from the logboat.
[src:charge-controller/boat] There are examples of logboats that have been expanded: by deforming the hull under heat, by raising the sides with added planks, or by splitting down the middle and adding a central plank to widen it.
[src:charge-controller/boat] (Some of these methods have been in quite recent use – there is no simple developmental sequence).
[src:charge-controller/boat] The earliest known plank-built boats are from the Nile, dating to the third millennium BC.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Outside Egypt, the next earliest are from England.
[src:charge-controller/boat] The Ferriby boats are dated to the early second millennium BC and the end of the third millennium BC.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Plank-built boats require a level of woodworking technology that was first available in the Neolithic with more complex versions only becoming achievable in the Bronze Age.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Boats can be categorized by their means of propulsion.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Powered by the crew-members on board, using oars, paddles or a punting pole or quant.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Towed – either by humans or animals from a river or canal bank (or in very shallow water, by walking on the sea or river bed) or by another vessel.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Powered by machinery, such as internal combustion engines, steam engines, or by batteries and an electric motor.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Any one vessel may use more than one of these methods at different times or in combination.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Several large vessels are usually referred to as boats.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Other types of large vessels which are traditionally called boats include Great Lakes freighters, riverboats, and ferryboats.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Though large enough to carry their own boats and heavy cargo, these vessels are designed for operation on inland or protected coastal waters.
[src:charge-controller/boat] The hull is the main, and in some cases only, structural component of a boat.
[src:charge-controller/boat] The keel is a boat's "backbone", a lengthwise structural member to which the perpendicular frames are fixed.
[src:charge-controller/boat] On some boats, a deck covers the hull, in part or whole.
[src:charge-controller/boat] While a ship often has several decks, a boat is unlikely to have more than one.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Above the deck are often lifelines connected to stanchions, bulwarks, perhaps topped by gunnels, or some combination of the two.
[src:charge-controller/boat] A cabin may protrude above the deck forward, aft, along the centerline, or cover much of the length of the boat.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Vertical structures dividing the internal spaces are known as bulkheads.
[src:charge-controller/boat] The forward end of a boat is called the bow, the aft end the stern.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Facing forward the right side is referred to as starboard and the left side as port.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Until the mid-19th century, most boats were made of natural materials, primarily wood, although bark and animal skins were also used.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Early boats include the birch bark canoe, the animal hide-covered kayak and coracle and the dugout canoe made from a single log.
[src:charge-controller/boat] By the mid-19th century, some boats had been built with iron or steel frames but still planked in wood.
[src:charge-controller/boat] In 1855, ferro-cement boat construction was patented by the French, who coined the name "ferciment".
[src:charge-controller/boat] This is a system by which a steel or iron wire framework is built in the shape of a boat's hull and covered over with cement.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Reinforced with bulkheads and other internal structures, it is strong but heavy, easily repaired, and, if sealed properly, will not leak or corrode.
[src:charge-controller/boat] As the forests of Britain and Europe continued to be over-harvested to supply the keels of larger wooden boats, and the Bessemer process (patented in 1855) reduced the cost of steel, steel ships and boats became more common.
[src:charge-controller/boat] By the 1930s, boats built entirely of steel, from frames to plating, were replacing wooden boats in many industrial uses and fishing fleets.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Private recreational steel boats remain uncommon.
[src:charge-controller/boat] In 1895, WH Mullins produced steel boats of galvanized iron, and by 1930, became the world's largest producer of pleasure boats.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Mullins also offered aluminium boats from 1895 through 1899 and once again in the 1920s, but it was not until the mid-20th century that aluminium gained widespread popularity.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Though much more expensive than steel, certain aluminum alloys do not corrode in salt water, allowing them to carry loads comparable to steel at much lower weight.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Around the mid-1960s, boats made of fiberglass (aka "glass fiber") became popular, especially for recreational boats.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Fiberglass is also known as "GRP" (glass-reinforced plastic) in the UK and "FRP" (fiber-reinforced plastic) in the US.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Fiberglass boats are strong and do not rust, corrode, or rot.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Instead, they are susceptible to structural degradation from sunlight and temperature extremes over their lifespan.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Fiberglass structures can be made stiffer with sandwich panels, where the fiberglass encloses a lightweight core such as balsa wood or foam.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Cold molding is a modern construction method that uses wood as the structural component.
[src:charge-controller/boat] In a single cold-molding process, very thin strips of wood are layered over a form.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Each layer is coated with resin, then another layer is laid on top at a 90-degree angle.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Subsequent layers may be stapled or otherwise mechanically fastened to the previous layer, or weighted or vacuum-bagged to provide compression and stabilization until the resin sets.
[src:charge-controller/boat] An alternative process uses thin plywood sheets shaped over a disposable male mold and coated with epoxy.
[src:charge-controller/boat] A boat displaces its weight in water, regardless of whether it is made of wood, steel, fiberglass, or even concrete.
[src:charge-controller/boat] If weight is added to the boat, the volume of the hull submerged below the waterline will increase to keep the weight above and below the surface balanced.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Boats have a natural or designed level of buoyancy.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Exceeding it will cause the boat first to ride lower in the water, second to take on water more readily than when properly loaded, and ultimately, if overloaded by any combination of structure, cargo, and water, sink.
[src:charge-controller/boat] As commercial vessels must be correctly loaded to be safe, and as the sea becomes less buoyant in brackish areas such as the Baltic, the Plimsoll line was introduced to prevent overloading.
[src:charge-controller/boat] Since 1998, all new leisure boats and barges built in Europe between 2.5m and 24m must comply with the EU's Recreational Craft Directive (RCD).
[src:charge-controller/boat] Europe is the main producer of recreational boats (the second-largest producer in the world is Poland).
[src:charge-controller/boat] European brands are known all over the world – in fact, these are the brands that created RCD and set the standard for shipyards around the world.
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] A **charge controller**, **charge regulator** or **battery regulator** limits the rate at which electric current is added to or drawn from electric batteries to protect against electrical overload, overcharging, and may protect against overvoltage.
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] This prevents conditions that reduce battery performance or lifespan and may pose a safety risk.
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] It may also prevent completely draining ("deep discharging") a battery, or perform controlled discharges, depending on the battery technology, to protect battery life.
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] The terms "charge controller" or "charge regulator" may refer to either a stand-alone device, or to control circuitry integrated within a battery pack, battery-powered device, and/or battery charger.
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] Charge controllers are sold to consumers as separate devices, often in conjunction with solar or wind power generators, for uses such as RV, boat, and off-the-grid home battery storage systems.
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] In solar applications, charge controllers may also be called solar regulators or solar charge controllers.
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] Some charge controllers / solar regulators have additional features, such as a low voltage disconnect (LVD), a separate circuit which powers down the load when the batteries become overly discharged (some battery chemistries are such that over-discharge can ruin the battery).
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] A **series charge controller** or **series regulator** disables further current flow into batteries when they are full.
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] A **shunt charge controller** or **shunt regulator** diverts excess electricity to an auxiliary or "shunt" load, such as an electric water heater, when batteries are full.
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] Simple charge controllers stop charging a battery when they exceed a set high voltage level, and re-enable charging when battery voltage drops back below that level.
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] Pulse-width modulation (PWM) and maximum power point tracker (MPPT) technologies are more electronically sophisticated, adjusting charging rates depending on the battery's level, to allow charging closer to its maximum capacity.
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] A charge controller with MPPT capability frees the system designer from closely matching available PV voltage to battery voltage.
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] Considerable efficiency gains can be achieved, particularly when the PV array is located at some distance from the battery.
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] By way of example, a 150 volt PV array connected to an MPPT charge controller can be used to charge a 24 or 48 volt battery.
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] Higher array voltage means lower array current, so the savings in wiring costs can more than pay for the controller.
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] Charge controllers may also monitor battery temperature to prevent overheating.
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] Some charge controller systems also display data, transmit data to remote displays, and data logging to track electric flow over time.
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] Circuitry that functions as a charge regulator controller may consist of several electrical components, or may be encapsulated in a single microchip, an integrated circuit (IC) usually called a charge controller IC or charge control IC.
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] Due to limitations in currents that copper wires could safely handle, charging protocols have been developed to allow the end device to request elevated voltages for increasing the power throughput without increasing heat in the wires.
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] The arriving voltage is then converted down to the battery's optimum charging voltage inside the end device.
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] The two most widely used standards are *Quick Charge* by Qualcomm and *Pump Express* by MediaTek.
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] The 2014 and 2015 versions of Pump Express, *Pump Express Plus* and *Pump Express Plus 2.0*, differ from by communicating voltage requests to the charger using current modulation signals through the main USB power lanes (*VBUS*) rather than negotiating through the USB 2.0 data lanes.
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] Pump Express Plus supports elevated voltage levels of 7, 9 and 12 volts, whereas the specification for Quick Charge 2.0 lacks the 7-volt level.
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] A 20-volt level was added in a revision named "class B" of the specification.
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] The voltage range of the successor Pump Express Plus 2.0 is between 5 volts and 20 volts, with 0.5 volts steps.
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] The Quick Charge 3.0 protocol supports finer-grain voltage levels with 0.2 volts steps and has a lower minimum voltage of approximately 3.3 volts.
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] According to *PocketNow*, Quick Charge 3.0 starts at 3.2 volts with 0.2 volts between each step and goes up to 20 V (3.2 V, 3.4 V, 4.6 V, ..., 19.8 V, 20 V).
[src:charge-controller/charge-controller] The site "powerbankexpert.com" claims that the protocol has a minimum voltage of 3.6 volts.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] A **communication protocol** is a system of rules that allows two or more entities of a communications system to transmit information.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The protocol defines the rules, syntax, semantics, and synchronization of communication and possible error recovery methods.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Protocols may be implemented by hardware, software, or a combination of both.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Communicating systems use well-defined formats for exchanging various messages.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Each message has an exact meaning intended to elicit a response from a range of possible responses predetermined for that particular situation.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The specified behavior is typically independent of how it is to be implemented.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Communication protocols have to be agreed upon by the parties involved.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] To reach an agreement, a protocol may be developed into a technical standard.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] A programming language describes the same for computations, so there is a close analogy between protocols and programming languages: *protocols are to communication what programming languages are to computations*.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] An alternate formulation states that *protocols are to communication what algorithms are to computation*.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Multiple protocols often describe different aspects of a single communication.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] A group of protocols designed to work together is known as a protocol suite; when implemented in software, they are a protocol stack.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Some of the most well-known communication protocols are those related to the Internet, web, and email, which are developed and published by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF), and World Wide Web Consortium.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Many wired and wireless protocols are also well known, such as Ethernet, Bluetooth, and of course mobile phone standards.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] These are mostly handled by the IEEE (Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers, e.g., Ethernet).
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] There is also the ITU-T, which handles telecommunications protocols & formats for the public switched telephone network (PSTN).
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] As the PSTN and Internet converge, many protocols are trending towards convergence.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) handles many other types.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] They published their work the following year.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] On the ARPANET, the starting point for host-to-host communication in 1969 was the 1822 protocol, written by Bob Kahn, which defined the transmission of messages to an IMP.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The Network Control Program (NCP) for the ARPANET, developed by Steve Crocker and other graduate students including Jon Postel, was first implemented in 1970.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The NCP interface allowed application software to connect across the ARPANET by implementing higher-level communication protocols, an early example of the *protocol layering* concept.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The CYCLADES network, designed by Louis Pouzin in the early 1970s, was the first to implement the end-to-end principle, and make the hosts responsible for the reliable delivery of data on a packet-switched network, rather than this being a service of the network itself.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] His team was the first to tackle the highly complex problem of providing user applications with a reliable virtual circuit service while using a best-effort service, an early contribution to what will be the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Bob Metcalfe and others at Xerox PARC outlined the idea of Ethernet and the PARC Universal Packet (PUP) for internetworking.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Research in the early 1970s by Bob Kahn and Vint Cerf led to the formulation of the Transmission Control Program (TCP).
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Its RFC 675 specification was written by Cerf with Yogen Dalal and Carl Sunshine in December 1974, still a monolithic design at this time.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The International Network Working Group agreed on a connectionless datagram standard, which was presented to the CCITT in 1975 but was not adopted by the CCITT nor by the ARPANET.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Separate international research, particularly the work of Rémi Després, contributed to the development of the X.25 standard, based on virtual circuits, which was adopted by the CCITT in 1976.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Computer manufacturers developed proprietary protocols such as IBM's Systems Network Architecture (SNA), Digital Equipment Corporation's DECnet and Xerox Network Systems.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] TCP software was redesigned as a modular protocol stack, referred to as *TCP/IP.* This was installed on SATNET in 1982 and on the ARPANET in January 1983.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The development of a complete Internet protocol suite by 1989, as outlined in RFC 1122 and RFC 1123, laid the foundation for the growth of TCP/IP as a comprehensive protocol suite as the core component of the emerging Internet.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] International work on a reference model for communication standards led to the OSI model, published in 1984.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] For a period in the late 1980s and early 1990s, engineers, organizations and nations became polarized over the issue of which standard, the OSI model or the Internet protocol suite, would result in the best and most robust computer networks.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The information exchanged between devices through a network or other media is governed by rules and conventions that can be set out in communication protocol specifications.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The nature of communication, the actual data exchanged and any state-dependent behaviors, is defined by these specifications.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] In digital computing systems, the rules can be expressed by algorithms and data structures.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Protocols are to communication what algorithms or programming languages are to computations.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Operating systems usually contain a set of cooperating processes that manipulate shared data to communicate with each other.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] This communication is governed by well-understood protocols, which can be embedded in the process code itself.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] In contrast, because there is no shared memory, communicating systems have to communicate with each other using a shared transmission medium.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Transmission is not necessarily reliable, and individual systems may use different hardware or operating systems.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] To implement a networking protocol, the protocol software modules are interfaced with a framework implemented on the machine's operating system.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] This framework implements the networking functionality of the operating system.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] When protocol algorithms are expressed in a portable programming language the protocol software may be made operating system independent.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The best-known frameworks are the TCP/IP model and the OSI model.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] This gave rise to the concept of layered protocols, which nowadays forms the basis of protocol design.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Systems typically do not use a single protocol to handle a transmission.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Instead, they use a set of cooperating protocols, sometimes called a protocol suite.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Some of the best-known protocol suites are TCP/IP, IPX/SPX, X.25, AX.25 and AppleTalk.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The protocols can be arranged based on functionality in groups; for instance, there is a group of transport protocols.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The functionalities are mapped onto the layers, each layer solving a distinct class of problems relating to, for instance: application-, transport-, internet- and network interface-functions.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] To transmit a message, a protocol has to be selected from each layer.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The selection of the next protocol is accomplished by extending the message with a protocol selector for each layer.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Communication protocols define the representation of messages exchanged between communicating systems.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Common approaches to message encoding use text or binary representations.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] A **text-based protocol** or **plain text protocol** represents its messages in human-readable format, often in plain text encoded in a machine-readable encoding such as ASCII or UTF-8, or in structured text-based formats such as Intel hex format, XML or JSON.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The immediate human readability stands in contrast with binary message representations, which have inherent benefits for use in a computer environment (such as ease of mechanical parsing and improved bandwidth utilization).
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Network applications have various methods of encapsulating data.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] One method very common with Internet protocols is a text-oriented message representation that transmits requests and responses as lines of ASCII text, terminated by a newline character (and usually a carriage return character).
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Examples of protocols that use plain, human-readable text for their commands are FTP (File Transfer Protocol), SMTP (Simple Mail Transfer Protocol), early versions of HTTP (Hypertext Transfer Protocol), and the finger protocol.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Text-based message representations are typically easier for humans to inspect and interpret, and are therefore suitable whenever human inspection of protocol contents is required, such as during debugging and during early protocol development design phases.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] A **binary protocol** uses a message representation that may utilize all values of a byte, as opposed to a text-based representation, which is limited to values corresponding to characters in a character encoding such as ASCII or UTF-8.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Binary message representations are intended to be processed by machines rather than read directly by humans.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Binary protocols have the advantage of terseness, which translates into speed of transmission and interpretation.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Binary message representations have been used in modern standards such as EbXML, HTTP/2, HTTP/3, and EDOC.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] An interface in UML may also be considered a binary protocol.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Getting the data across a network is only part of the problem for a protocol.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The data received has to be evaluated in the context of the progress of the conversation, so a protocol must include rules describing the context.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] These kinds of rules are said to express the *syntax* of the communication.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Other rules determine whether the data is meaningful for the context in which the exchange takes place.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] These kinds of rules are said to express the *semantics* of the communication.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Messages are sent and received on communicating systems to establish communication.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Protocols should therefore specify rules governing the transmission.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Digital message bitstrings are exchanged.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The bitstrings are divided in fields and each field carries information relevant to the protocol.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The actual message is carried in the payload.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The header area contains the fields relevant to the operation of the protocol.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] (MTU) are divided in pieces of appropriate size.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Addresses are used to identify both the sender and the intended receiver(s).
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The addresses are carried in the header area of the bitstrings, allowing the receivers to determine whether the bitstrings are of interest and should be processed or should be ignored.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Usually, some address values have special meanings.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] s address could be taken to mean an addressing of all stations on the network, so sending to this address would result in a broadcast on the local network.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Sometimes protocols need to map addresses of one scheme on addresses of another scheme.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] For instance, to translate a logical IP address specified by the application to an Ethernet MAC address.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] to the intended receiver(s) need to forward messages on behalf of the sender.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] On the Internet, the networks are connected using routers.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Error detection is necessary on networks where data corruption is possible.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] In a common approach, a CRC of the data area is added to the end of packets, making it possible for the receiver to detect differences caused by corruption.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The receiver rejects the packets on CRC differences and arranges somehow for retransmission.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Acknowledgments are sent from receivers back to their respective senders.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Packets may be lost on the network or be delayed in transit.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] To cope with this, under some protocols, a sender may expect an acknowledgment of correct reception from the receiver within a certain amount of time.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] , the sender may need to retransmit the information.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] In case of a permanently broken link, the retransmission has no effect, so the number of retransmissions is limited.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Exceeding the retry limit is considered an error.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] where two parties respectively simultaneously transmit or wish to transmit.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] If long bitstrings are divided into pieces and then sent on the network individually, the pieces may get lost or delayed or, on some types of networks, take different routes to their destination.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] As a result, pieces may arrive out of sequence.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Retransmissions can result in duplicate pieces.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] By marking the pieces with sequence information at the sender, the receiver can determine what was lost or duplicated, ask for necessary retransmissions and reassemble the original message.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Flow control is needed when the sender transmits faster than the receiver or intermediate network equipment can process the transmissions.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Flow control can be implemented by messaging from receiver to sender.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Communicating processes or state machines employ queues (or "buffers"), usually FIFO queues, to deal with the messages in the order sent, and may sometimes have multiple queues with different prioritization.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Systems engineering principles have been applied to create a set of common network protocol design principles.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The design of complex protocols often involves decomposition into simpler, cooperating protocols.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Such a set of cooperating protocols is sometimes called a protocol family or a protocol suite, within a conceptual framework.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Communicating systems operate concurrently.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] An important aspect of concurrent programming is the synchronization of software for receiving and transmitting messages of communication in proper sequencing.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Concurrent programming has traditionally been a topic in operating systems theory texts.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Formal verification seems indispensable because concurrent programs are notorious for the hidden and sophisticated bugs they contain.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] A mathematical approach to the study of concurrency and communication is referred to as communicating sequential processes (CSP).
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Concurrency can also be modeled using finite-state machines, such as Mealy and Moore machines.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Mealy and Moore machines are in use as design tools in digital electronics systems encountered in the form of hardware used in telecommunication or electronic devices in general.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The literature presents numerous analogies between computer communication and programming.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] In analogy, a transfer mechanism of a protocol is comparable to a central processing unit (CPU).
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The framework introduces rules that allow the programmer to design cooperating protocols independently of one another.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] In modern protocol design, protocols are layered to form a protocol stack.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Layering is a design principle that divides the protocol design task into smaller steps, each of which accomplishes a specific part, interacting with the other parts of the protocol only in a small number of well-defined ways.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Layering allows the parts of a protocol to be designed and tested without a combinatorial explosion of cases, keeping each design relatively simple.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The communication protocols in use on the Internet are designed to function in diverse and complex settings.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Internet protocols are designed for simplicity and modularity and fit into a coarse hierarchy of functional layers defined in the Internet Protocol Suite.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The first two cooperating protocols, the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) and the Internet Protocol (IP) resulted from the decomposition of the original Transmission Control Program, a monolithic communication protocol, into this layered communication suite.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The OSI model was developed internationally based on experience with networks that predated the Internet as a reference model for general communication with much stricter rules of protocol interaction and rigorous layering.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Typically, application software is built upon a robust data transport layer.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Underlying this transport layer is a datagram delivery and routing mechanism that is typically connectionless in the Internet.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Packet relaying across networks happens over another layer that involves only network link technologies, which are often specific to certain physical layer technologies, such as Ethernet.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Layering provides opportunities to exchange technologies when needed, for example, protocols are often stacked in a tunneling arrangement to accommodate the connection of dissimilar networks.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] For example, IP may be tunneled across an Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) network.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Protocol layering forms the basis of protocol design.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] It allows the decomposition of single, complex protocols into simpler, cooperating protocols.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The protocol layers each solve a distinct class of communication problems.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Together, the layers make up a layering scheme or model.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Computations deal with algorithms and data; Communication involves protocols and messages; So the analog of a data flow diagram is some kind of message flow diagram.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] To visualize protocol layering and protocol suites, a diagram of the message flows in and between two systems, A and B, is shown in figure 3.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The systems, A and B, both make use of the same protocol suite.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The vertical flows (and protocols) are in-system and the horizontal message flows (and protocols) are between systems.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The message flows are governed by rules, and data formats specified by protocols.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The blue lines mark the boundaries of the (horizontal) protocol layers.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The software supporting protocols has a layered organization, and its relationship with protocol layering is shown in figure 5.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] To send a message on system A, the top-layer software module interacts with the module directly below it and hands over the message to be encapsulated.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The lower module fills in the header data in accordance with the protocol it implements and interacts with the bottom module, which sends the message over the communications channel to the bottom module of system B.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] On the receiving system B the reverse happens, so ultimately the message gets delivered in its original form to the top module of system B.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Program translation is divided into subproblems.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] As a result, the translation software is layered as well, allowing the software layers to be designed independently.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The same approach can be seen in the TCP/IP layering.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The modules below the application layer are generally considered part of the operating system.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Passing data between these modules is much less expensive than passing data between an application program and the transport layer.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The boundary between the application layer and the transport layer is called the operating system boundary.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Strictly adhering to a layered model, a practice known as strict layering, is not always the best approach to networking.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Strict layering can have a negative impact on the performance of an implementation.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Commonly recurring problems in the design and implementation of communication protocols can be addressed by software design patterns.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Popular formal methods of describing communication syntax are Abstract Syntax Notation One (an ISO standard) and augmented Backus–Naur form (an IETF standard).
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] For communication to occur, protocols have to be selected.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The rules can be expressed by algorithms and data structures.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Hardware and operating system independence is enhanced by expressing the algorithms in a portable programming language.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Source independence of the specification provides wider interoperability.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Protocol standards are commonly created by obtaining the approval or support of a standards organization, which initiates the standardization process.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The members of the standards organization agree to adhere to the work result on a voluntary basis.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Often, the members are in control of large market shares relevant to the protocol, and in many cases, standards are enforced by law or the government because they are thought to serve an important public interest, so getting approval can be very important for the protocol.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The need for protocol standards can be shown by looking at what happened to the Binary Synchronous Communications (BSC) protocol invented by IBM.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] BSC is an early link-level protocol used to connect two separate nodes.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] It was originally not intended to be used in a multinode network, but doing so revealed several deficiencies of the protocol.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] In the absence of standardization, manufacturers and organizations felt free to enhance the protocol, creating incompatible versions on their networks.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] In some cases, this was deliberately done to discourage users from using equipment from other manufacturers.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] There are more than 50 variants of the original bi-sync protocol.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] One can assume that a standard would have prevented at least some of this from happening.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] In some cases, protocols gain market dominance without going through a standardization process.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Such protocols are referred to as *de facto standards*.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] De facto standards are common in emerging markets, niche markets, or markets that are monopolized (or oligopolized).
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] They can hold a market in a very negative grip, especially when used to scare away competition.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] From a historical perspective, standardization should be seen as a measure to counteract the ill effects of de facto standards.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Positive exceptions exist; a de facto standard operating system like Linux does not have this negative grip on its market because the sources are published and maintained in an open way, thus inviting competition.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Some of the standards organizations of relevance for communication protocols are the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), the International Telecommunication Union (ITU), the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE), and the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF).
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The IETF maintains the protocols in use on the Internet.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The IEEE controls many software and hardware protocols in the electronics industry for commercial and consumer devices.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The ITU is an umbrella organization of telecommunication engineers designing the public switched telephone network (PSTN), as well as many radio communication systems.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] For marine electronics, the NMEA standards are used.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) produces protocols and standards for Web technologies.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] International standards organizations are supposed to be more impartial than local organizations with a national or commercial self-interest to consider.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Standards organizations also do research and development for standards of the future.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] In practice, the standards organizations mentioned cooperate closely with each other.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Multiple standards bodies may be involved in the development of a protocol.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] In the ISO, the standardization process starts off with the commissioning of a sub-committee workgroup.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The workgroup issues working drafts and discussion documents to interested parties (including other standards bodies) in order to provoke discussion and comments.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] This will generate a lot of questions, much discussion and usually some disagreement.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] These comments are taken into account, and a *draft proposal* is produced by the working group.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] After feedback, modification, and compromise, the proposal reaches the status of a *draft international standard*, and ultimately an *international standard*.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] International standards are reissued periodically to address deficiencies and reflect changing views on the subject.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] A lesson learned from ARPANET, the predecessor of the Internet, was that protocols need a framework to operate.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] It is therefore important to develop a general-purpose, future-proof framework suitable for *structured protocols* (such as layered protocols) and their standardization.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] This would prevent protocol standards with overlapping functionality and would allow a clear definition of the responsibilities of a protocol at the different levels (layers).
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] This gave rise to the Open Systems Interconnection model (OSI model), which is used as a framework for the design of standard protocols and services conforming to the various layer specifications.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] In the OSI model, communicating systems are assumed to be connected by an underlying physical medium providing a basic transmission mechanism.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Each layer provides service to the layer above it using the services of the layer immediately below it.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The top layer provides services to the application process.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The layers communicate with each other by means of an interface, called a *service access point*.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Corresponding layers at each system are called *peer entities*.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] To communicate, two peer entities at a given layer use a protocol specific to that layer, which is implemented by using services of the layer below.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] For each layer, there are two types of standards: protocol standards defining how peer entities at a given layer communicate, and service standards defining how a given layer communicates with the layer above it.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] In contrast to the TCP/IP layering scheme, which assumes a connectionless network, RM/OSI assumed a connection-oriented network.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Connection-oriented networks are more suitable for wide area networks and connectionless networks are more suitable for local area networks.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Connection-oriented communication requires some form of session and (virtual) circuits, hence the (in the TCP/IP model lacking) session layer.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The constituent members of ISO were mostly concerned with wide area networks, so the development of RM/OSI concentrated on connection-oriented networks and connectionless networks were first mentioned in an addendum to RM/OSI and later incorporated into an update to RM/OSI.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] At the time, the IETF had to cope with this and the fact that the Internet needed protocols that simply were not there.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] As a result, the IETF developed its own standardization process based on "rough consensus and running code".
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The standardization process is described by RFC 2026.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Nowadays, the IETF has become a standards organization for the protocols in use on the Internet.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] RM/OSI has extended its model to include connectionless services, and because of this, both TCP and IP could be developed into international standards.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The *wire image* of a protocol is the information that a non-participant observer is able to glean from observing the protocol messages, including both information explicitly given meaning by the protocol, but also inferences made by the observer.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Unencrypted protocol metadata is one source making up the wire image, and side-channels including packet timing also contribute.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Different observers with different vantages may see different wire images.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The wire image is relevant to end-user privacy and the extensibility of the protocol.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] If some portion of the wire image is not cryptographically authenticated, it is subject to modification by intermediate parties (i.e., middleboxes), which can influence protocol operation.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Even if authenticated, if a portion is not encrypted, it will form part of the wire image, and intermediate parties may intervene depending on its content (e.g., dropping packets with particular flags).
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Signals deliberately intended for intermediary consumption may be left authenticated but unencrypted.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The wire image can be deliberately engineered, encrypting parts that intermediaries should not be able to observe and providing signals for what they should be able to.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] If provided signals are decoupled from the protocol's operation, they may become untrustworthy.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Benign network management and research are affected by metadata encryption; protocol designers must balance observability for operability and research against ossification resistance and end-user privacy.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Engineering the wire image and controlling what signals are provided to network elements was a "developing field" in 2023, according to the IAB.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Protocol ossification is the loss of flexibility, extensibility and evolvability of network protocols.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] This is largely due to middleboxes that are sensitive to the wire image of the protocol, and which can interrupt or interfere with messages that are valid but which the middlebox does not correctly recognize.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] This is a violation of the end-to-end principle.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Secondary causes include inflexibility in endpoint implementations of protocols.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Because of ossification, the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) and User Datagram Protocol (UDP) are the only practical choices for transport protocols on the Internet, and TCP itself has significantly ossified, making extension or modification of the protocol difficult.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Recommended methods of preventing ossification include encrypting protocol metadata, and ensuring that extension points are exercised and wire image variability is exhibited as fully as possible; remedying existing ossification requires coordination across protocol participants.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] QUIC is the first IETF transport protocol to have been designed with deliberate anti-ossification properties.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Classification schemes for protocols usually focus on the domain of use and function.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] As an example of domain of use, connection-oriented protocols and connectionless protocols are used on connection-oriented networks and connectionless networks, respectively.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] An example of function is a tunneling protocol, which is used to encapsulate packets in a high-level protocol so that the packets can be passed across a transport system using the high-level protocol.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] A *layering scheme* combines both function and domain of use.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The dominant layering schemes are the ones developed by the IETF and by ISO.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Despite the fact that the underlying assumptions of the layering schemes are different enough to warrant distinguishing the two, it is a common practice to compare the two by relating common protocols to the layers of the two schemes.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The layering scheme from the IETF is called *Internet layering* or *TCP/IP layering*.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] The layering scheme from ISO is called *the OSI model* or *ISO layering*.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] In networking equipment configuration, a term-of-art distinction is often drawn: The term *protocol* strictly refers to the transport layer, and the term *service* refers to protocols utilizing a *protocol* for transport.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] In the common case of TCP and UDP, services are distinguished by port numbers.
[src:charge-controller/communication-protocol] Conformance to these port numbers is voluntary, so in content inspection systems, the term *service* strictly refers to port numbers, and the term *application* is often used to refer to protocols identified through inspection signatures.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] An **electric current** is a flow of charged particles, such as electrons or ions, through an electrical conductor or space.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] It is defined as the net rate at which electric charge flows through a surface.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] The moving particles are called charge carriers, which may be of several types, depending on the conductor.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In electric circuits, the charge carriers are often electrons moving through a wire.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In semiconductors, the charge carriers can be electrons or holes.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In an electrolyte, the charge carriers are ions, while in plasma- an ionized gas- they are also ions and electrons.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In the International System of Units (SI), electric current is expressed in units of ampere (sometimes called an "amp", symbol A), which is equivalent to one coulomb per second.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] The ampere is an SI base unit and electric current is a base quantity in the International System of Quantities (ISQ).
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Electric current is also known as **amperage** and is measured using a device called an *ammeter*.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Electric currents create magnetic fields, which are used in motors, generators, inductors, and transformers.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In ordinary conductors, they cause Joule heating, which creates light in incandescent light bulbs.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Time-varying currents emit electromagnetic waves, which are used in telecommunications to broadcast information.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] The conventional symbol for current is *I*, which originates from the French phrase *intensité du courant* (current intensity).
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Current intensity is often referred to simply as *current*.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] The *I* symbol was used by André-Marie Ampère, after whom the unit of electric current is named, in formulating Ampère's force law (1820).
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] The notation travelled from France to Great Britain, where it became standard, although at least one journal did not change from using *C* to *I* until 1896.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] The conventional direction of current, also known as *conventional current*, is arbitrarily defined as the direction in which *positive* charges flow.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In a conductive material, the moving charged particles that constitute the electric current are called charge carriers.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In metals, which make up the wires and other conductors in most electrical circuits, the positively charged atomic nuclei of the atoms are held in a fixed position, and the negatively charged electrons are the charge carriers, free to move about in the metal.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In other materials, notably the semiconductors, the charge carriers can be positive *or* negative, depending on the dopant used.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Positive and negative charge carriers may even be present at the same time, as happens in an electrolyte in an electrochemical cell.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] A flow of positive charges gives the same electric current, and has the same effect in a circuit, as an equal flow of negative charges in the opposite direction.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Since current can be the flow of either positive or negative charges, or both, a convention is needed for the direction of current that is independent of the type of charge carriers.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Negatively charged carriers, such as the electrons (the charge carriers in metal wires and many other electronic circuit components), therefore flow in the opposite direction of conventional current flow in an electrical circuit.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] A current in a wire or circuit element can flow in either of two directions.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] When defining a variable I to represent the current, the direction representing positive current must be specified, usually by an arrow on the circuit schematic diagram.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] This is called the *reference direction* of the current I .
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] When analyzing electrical circuits, the actual direction of current through a specific circuit element is usually unknown until the analysis is completed.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Consequently, the reference directions of currents are often assigned arbitrarily.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] When the circuit is solved, a negative value for the current implies the actual direction of current through that circuit element is opposite that of the chosen reference direction.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Ohm's law states that the current through a conductor between two points is directly proportional to the potential difference across the two points.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] The constant of proportionality in this relationship is the resistance.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] where *I* is the current through the conductor in units of amperes, *V* is the potential difference measured *across* the conductor in units of volts, and *R* is the resistance of the conductor in units of ohms.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] More specifically, Ohm's law states that the *R* in this relation is constant, independent of the current.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In alternating current (AC) systems, the movement of electric charge periodically reverses direction.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] AC is the form of electric power most commonly delivered to businesses and residences.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] The usual waveform of an AC power circuit is a sine wave, though certain applications use alternative waveforms, such as triangular or square waves.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Audio and radio signals carried on electrical wires are also examples of alternating current.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] An important goal in these applications is recovery of information encoded (or *modulated*) onto the AC signal.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In contrast, direct current (DC) refers to a system in which electric charge moves in only one direction (sometimes called unidirectional flow).
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Direct current is produced by sources such as batteries, thermocouples, solar cells, and commutator-type electric machines of the dynamo type.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Alternating current can also be converted to direct current through use of a rectifier.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Direct current may flow in a conductor such as a wire, but can also flow through semiconductors, insulators, or even through a vacuum as in electron or ion beams.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] An old name for direct current was *galvanic current*.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Natural observable examples of electric current include lightning, static electric discharge, and the solar wind, the source of the polar auroras.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Man-made occurrences of electric current include the flow of conduction electrons in metal wires such as the overhead power lines that deliver electrical energy across long distances and the smaller wires within electrical and electronic equipment.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Eddy currents are electric currents that occur in conductors exposed to changing magnetic fields.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Similarly, electric currents occur, particularly in the surface, of conductors exposed to electromagnetic waves.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] When oscillating electric currents flow at the correct voltages within radio antennas, radio waves are generated.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In electronics, other forms of electric current include the flow of electrons through resistors or through the vacuum in a vacuum tube, the flow of ions inside a battery, and the flow of holes within metals and semiconductors.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] A biological example of current is the flow of ions in neurons and nerves, responsible for both thought and sensory perception.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Current can be measured using an ammeter.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Electric current can be directly measured with a galvanometer, but this method involves breaking the electrical circuit, which is sometimes inconvenient.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Current can also be measured without breaking the circuit by detecting the magnetic field associated with the current.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Joule heating, also known as *ohmic heating* and *resistive heating*, is the process of power dissipation by which the passage of an electric current through a conductor increases the internal energy of the conductor, converting thermodynamic work into heat.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] The phenomenon was first studied by James Prescott Joule in 1841.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Joule immersed a length of wire in a fixed mass of water and measured the temperature rise due to a known current through the wire for a 30 minute period.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] By varying the current and the length of the wire he deduced that the heat produced was proportional to the square of the current multiplied by the electrical resistance of the wire.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] This relationship is known as Joule's Law.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] The SI unit of energy was subsequently named the joule and given the symbol *J*.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] The commonly known SI unit of power, the watt (symbol: W), is equivalent to one joule per second.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In an electromagnet a coil of wires behaves like a magnet when an electric current flows through it.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] When the current is switched off, the coil loses its magnetism immediately.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Electric current produces a magnetic field.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] The magnetic field can be visualized as a pattern of circular field lines surrounding the wire that persists as long as there is current.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Magnetic fields can also be used to make electric currents.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] When a changing magnetic field is applied to a conductor, an electromotive force (EMF) is induced, which starts an electric current, when there is a suitable path.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] When an electric current flows in a suitably shaped conductor at radio frequencies, radio waves can be generated.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] These travel at the speed of light and can cause electric currents in distant conductors.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In metallic solids, electric charge flows by means of electrons, from lower to higher electrical potential.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In other media, any stream of charged objects (ions, for example) may constitute an electric current.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] To provide a definition of current independent of the type of charge carriers, *conventional current* is defined as moving in the same direction as the positive charge flow.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] So, in metals where the charge carriers (electrons) are negative, conventional current is in the opposite direction to the overall electron movement.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In conductors where the charge carriers are positive, conventional current is in the same direction as the charge carriers.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In a vacuum, a beam of ions or electrons may be formed.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In other conductive materials, the electric current is due to the flow of both positively and negatively charged particles at the same time.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In still others, the current is entirely due to positive charge flow.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] For example, the electric currents in electrolytes are flows of positively and negatively charged ions.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In a common lead-acid electrochemical cell, electric currents are composed of positive hydronium ions flowing in one direction, and negative sulfate ions flowing in the other.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Electric currents in sparks or plasma are flows of electrons as well as positive and negative ions.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In ice and in certain solid electrolytes, the electric current is entirely composed of flowing ions.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In a metal, some of the outer electrons in each atom are not bound to the individual molecules as they are in molecular solids, or in full bands as they are in insulating materials, but are free to move within the metal lattice.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] These conduction electrons serve as charge carriers that can flow through the conductor as an electric current when an electric field is present.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Metals are particularly conductive because there are many of these free electrons.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] With no external electric field applied, these electrons move about randomly due to thermal energy but, on average, there is zero net current within the metal.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] At room temperature, the average speed of these random motions is 106 metres per second.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Given a surface through which a metal wire passes, electrons move in both directions across the surface at an equal rate.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] As George Gamow wrote in his popular science book, *One, Two, Three...Infinity* (1947), "The metallic substances differ from all other materials by the fact that the outer shells of their atoms are bound rather loosely, and often let one of their electrons go free.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Thus the interior of a metal is filled up with a large number of unattached electrons that travel aimlessly around like a crowd of displaced persons.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] When a metal wire is connected across the two terminals of a DC voltage source such as a battery, the source places an electric field across the conductor.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] The moment contact is made, the free electrons of the conductor are forced to drift toward the positive terminal under the influence of this field.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] The free electrons are therefore the charge carrier in a typical solid conductor.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] For a steady flow of charge through a surface, the current *I* (in amperes) can be calculated with the following equation: $I={Q \over t}\,,$ where *Q* is the electric charge transferred through the surface over a time *t*.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] If *Q* and *t* are measured in coulombs and seconds respectively, *I* is in amperes.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Electric currents in electrolytes are flows of electrically charged particles (ions).
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] For example, if an electric field is placed across a solution of Na+ and Cl− (and conditions are right) the sodium ions move towards the negative electrode (cathode), while the chloride ions move towards the positive electrode (anode).
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Reactions take place at both electrode surfaces, neutralizing each ion.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Water-ice and certain solid electrolytes called *proton conductors* contain positive hydrogen ions ("protons") that are mobile.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In these materials, electric currents are composed of moving protons, as opposed to the moving electrons in metals.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In certain electrolyte mixtures, brightly coloured ions are the moving electric charges.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] The slow progress of the colour makes the current visible.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In air and other ordinary gases below the breakdown field, the dominant source of electrical conduction is via relatively few mobile ions produced by radioactive gases, ultraviolet light, or cosmic rays.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Since the electrical conductivity is low, gases are dielectrics or insulators.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] However, once the applied electric field approaches the breakdown value, free electrons become sufficiently accelerated by the electric field to create additional free electrons by colliding, and ionizing, neutral gas atoms or molecules in a process called avalanche breakdown.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] The breakdown process forms a plasma that contains enough mobile electrons and positive ions to make it an electrical conductor.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In the process, it forms a light emitting conductive path, such as a spark, arc or lightning.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Plasma is the state of matter where some of the electrons in a gas are stripped or "ionized" from their molecules or atoms.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] A plasma can be formed by high temperature, or by application of a high electric or alternating magnetic field as noted above.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Due to their lower mass, the electrons in a plasma accelerate more quickly in response to an electric field than the heavier positive ions, and hence carry the bulk of the current.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] The free ions recombine to create new chemical compounds (for example, breaking atmospheric oxygen into single oxygen [O2 → 2O], which then recombine creating ozone [O3]).
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Since a "perfect vacuum" contains no charged particles, it normally behaves as a perfect insulator.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] However, metal electrode surfaces can cause a region of the vacuum to become conductive by injecting free electrons or ions through either field electron emission or thermionic emission.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Thermionic emission occurs when the thermal energy exceeds the metal's work function, while field electron emission occurs when the electric field at the surface of the metal is high enough to cause tunneling, which results in the ejection of free electrons from the metal into the vacuum.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Externally heated electrodes are often used to generate an electron cloud as in the filament or indirectly heated cathode of vacuum tubes.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Cold electrodes can also spontaneously produce electron clouds via thermionic emission when small incandescent regions (called *cathode spots* or *anode spots*) are formed.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] These are incandescent regions of the electrode surface that are created by a localized high current.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] These regions may be initiated by field electron emission, but are then sustained by localized thermionic emission once a vacuum arc forms.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] These small electron-emitting regions can form quite rapidly, even explosively, on a metal surface subjected to a high electrical field.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Vacuum tubes and krytrons are some of the electronic switching and amplifying devices based on vacuum conductivity.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Superconductivity is a phenomenon of exactly zero electrical resistance and expulsion of magnetic fields occurring in certain materials when cooled below a characteristic critical temperature.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] It was discovered by Heike Kamerlingh Onnes on April 8, 1911 in Leiden.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Like ferromagnetism and atomic spectral lines, superconductivity is a quantum mechanical phenomenon.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] It is characterized by the Meissner effect, the complete ejection of magnetic field lines from the interior of the superconductor as it transitions into the superconducting state.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] The occurrence of the Meissner effect indicates that superconductivity cannot be understood simply as the idealization of *perfect conductivity* in classical physics.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In a semiconductor it is sometimes useful to think of the current as due to the flow of positive "holes" (the mobile positive charge carriers that are places where the semiconductor crystal is missing a valence electron).
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] This is the case in a p-type semiconductor.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] A semiconductor has electrical conductivity intermediate in magnitude between that of a conductor and an insulator.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] This means a conductivity roughly in the range of 10−2 to 104 siemens per centimeter (S⋅cm−1).
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In the classic crystalline semiconductors, electrons can have energies only within certain bands (i.e. ranges of levels of energy).
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Energetically, these bands are located between the energy of the ground state, the state in which electrons are tightly bound to the atomic nuclei of the material, and the free electron energy, the latter describing the energy required for an electron to escape entirely from the material.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] The energy bands each correspond to many discrete quantum states of the electrons, and most of the states with low energy (closer to the nucleus) are occupied, up to a particular band called the *valence band*.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] The ease of exciting electrons in the semiconductor from the valence band to the conduction band depends on the band gap between the bands.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] The size of this energy band gap serves as an arbitrary dividing line (roughly 4 eV) between semiconductors and insulators.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] With covalent bonds, an electron moves by hopping to a neighboring bond.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] The Pauli exclusion principle requires that the electron be lifted into the higher anti-bonding state of that bond.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] For delocalized states, for example in one dimension – that is in a nanowire, for every energy there is a state with electrons flowing in one direction and another state with the electrons flowing in the other.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] For a net current to flow, more states for one direction than for the other direction must be occupied.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] For this to occur, energy is required, as in the semiconductor the next higher states lie above the band gap.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Often this is stated as: full bands do not contribute to the electrical conductivity.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] However, as a semiconductor's temperature rises above absolute zero, there is more energy in the semiconductor to spend on lattice vibration and on exciting electrons into the conduction band.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] The current-carrying electrons in the conduction band are known as *free electrons*, though they are often simply called *electrons* if that is clear in context.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Current density is the rate at which charge passes through a chosen unit area.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] It is defined as a vector whose magnitude is the current per unit cross-sectional area.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] As discussed in Reference direction, the direction is arbitrary.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Conventionally, if the moving charges are positive, then the current density has the same sign as the velocity of the charges.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] For negative charges, the sign of the current density is opposite to the velocity of the charges.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In SI units, current density (symbol: j) is expressed in the SI base units of amperes per square metre.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] In linear materials such as metals, and under low frequencies, the current density across the conductor surface is uniform.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] where I is the current, measured in amperes; V is the potential difference, measured in volts; and R is the resistance, measured in ohms.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] For alternating currents, especially at higher frequencies, skin effect causes the current to spread unevenly across the conductor cross-section, with higher density near the surface, thus increasing the apparent resistance.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] The mobile charged particles within a conductor move constantly in random directions, like the particles of a gas.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] (More accurately, a Fermi gas.) To create a net flow of charge, the particles must also move together with an average drift rate.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Electrons are the charge carriers in most metals and they follow an erratic path, bouncing from atom to atom, but generally drifting in the opposite direction of the electric field.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Typically, electric charges in solids flow slowly.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] For example, in a copper wire of cross-section 0.5 mm2, carrying a current of 5 A, the drift velocity of the electrons is on the order of a millimetre per second.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] To take a different example, in the near-vacuum inside a cathode ray tube, the electrons travel in near-straight lines at about a tenth of the speed of light.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] Any accelerating electric charge, and therefore any changing electric current, gives rise to an electromagnetic wave that propagates at very high speed *outside* the surface of the conductor.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] This speed is usually a significant fraction of the speed of light, as can be deduced from Maxwell's equations, and is therefore many times faster than the drift velocity of the electrons.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] For example, in AC power lines, the waves of electromagnetic energy propagate through the space between the wires, moving from a source to a distant load, even though the electrons in the wires only move back and forth over a tiny distance.
[src:charge-controller/electric-current] The ratio of the speed of the surrounding electromagnetic wave to the speed of light in free space is called the velocity factor, and depends on the electromagnetic properties of the conductor and the insulating materials surrounding it, and on their shape and size.
